1. Basics (Every DevOps Engineer Must Know)

What is Kubernetes (K8s)?

Open-source container orchestration platform.

Automates deployment, scaling, healing, networking of containerized apps.

Created by Google, now maintained by CNCF.

Core Components

Control Plane

API Server â†’ entrypoint (kubectl â†’ API calls).

etcd â†’ key-value store for cluster state.

Controller Manager â†’ reconciles desired vs actual state.

Scheduler â†’ assigns pods to nodes.

Worker Nodes

kubelet â†’ talks to API server, runs containers.

kube-proxy â†’ manages networking/routing.

Container runtime â†’ Docker/Containerd/CRI-O.

Basic Resources

Pod â†’ smallest deployable unit (1+ containers).

ReplicaSet â†’ ensures desired pod replicas.

Deployment â†’ manages pods + ReplicaSets (rolling updates).

Service â†’ exposes pods: ClusterIP, NodePort, LoadBalancer.

Namespace â†’ logical separation of resources.

ConfigMap & Secret â†’ configs & sensitive data.

Basic Commands

kubectl get nodes
kubectl get pods -A
kubectl describe pod <pod>
kubectl logs <pod>
kubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash
kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml
kubectl delete -f deployment.yaml


âœ… Must-know foundation.

ğŸ”¹ 2. Medium-Level Concepts (Practical Usage)

Networking

ClusterIP â†’ default, internal-only.

NodePort â†’ expose service on each nodeâ€™s port.

LoadBalancer â†’ external access via cloud LB.

Ingress â†’ single LB with host/path-based routing.

Storage

Volumes â†’ pod-scoped, lifecycle-bound.

PersistentVolume (PV) â†’ cluster-wide storage resource.

PersistentVolumeClaim (PVC) â†’ podâ€™s request for storage.

StorageClass â†’ dynamic provisioning.

Scaling

HPA (Horizontal Pod Autoscaler) â†’ scales pods based on CPU/memory/custom metrics.

VPA (Vertical Pod Autoscaler) â†’ adjusts pod resources.

Cluster Autoscaler â†’ scales nodes dynamically.

Labels & Selectors

Labels â†’ key-value identifiers.

Selectors â†’ group resources by labels.

âœ… Prepares you for daily production work.

ğŸ”¹ 3. Advanced Concepts (FAANG-Level)

Workload Controllers

DaemonSet â†’ 1 pod per node (logging/monitoring agents).

StatefulSet â†’ ordered, stable identity (DBs, Kafka).

Job / CronJob â†’ one-time or scheduled workloads.

Advanced Networking

Network Policies â†’ control pod-to-pod communication.

CNI Plugins â†’ Calico, Flannel, Cilium.

Service Mesh â†’ Istio/Linkerd (traffic control, mTLS).

Security

RBAC â†’ Roles, ClusterRoles, Bindings.

Service Accounts â†’ identity for pods.

Pod Security Standards (PSS) â†’ baseline, restricted.

Secrets Encryption â†’ encrypt secrets in etcd.

Admission Controllers â†’ enforce policies.

Observability

Metrics Server â†’ CPU/memory metrics.

Prometheus + Grafana â†’ monitoring & alerts.

EFK/ELK Stack â†’ centralized logging.

Jaeger/Zipkin â†’ distributed tracing.

CI/CD & GitOps

Deploy via Jenkins, GitHub Actions.

GitOps tools: ArgoCD, Flux.

Helm / Kustomize for templating.

Cluster Management

Namespaces per environment (dev/stage/prod).

Multi-cluster management â†’ Rancher, Anthos.

Upgrades with zero downtime.

âœ… These are senior-level interview favorites.

ğŸ”¹ 4. Real-World DevOps Scenarios

Blue-Green Deployment â†’ run v1 & v2, switch traffic.

Canary Deployment â†’ roll out to % of users first.

Rolling Updates/Rollbacks â†’ zero-downtime updates.

Secrets Rotation â†’ integrate with Vault/AWS Secrets Manager.

Multi-Cluster Setup â†’ HA across regions.

Disaster Recovery â†’ etcd backup/restore.

Resource Limits â†’ enforce CPU/memory quotas.

Cost Optimization â†’ scale-to-zero, spot nodes.

Hybrid Cloud â†’ workloads across AWS + GCP + Azure.

âœ… Shows real production experience.

ğŸ”¹ 5. High Availability (HA) & Security

HA Setup

Multi-master clusters with etcd quorum.

Load balancer in front of API servers.

etcd backups (snapshot + restore).

Security Best Practices

Use RBAC strictly.

Run pods as non-root.

Network policies â†’ whitelist traffic.

Enable audit logging.

Rotate secrets & certificates.

